item.caption: MRI cervical spine without contrast (09/14/2015 8:39 AM)

td.paragraph: IMPRESSION: Multilevel mild to moderate cervical degenerative changes, and negative findings for focal neural impingement.
TECHNIQUE:Sagittal T1, sagittal T2, sagittal STIR, axial T2, bilateral oblique sagittal T2, and coronal scout sequences are obtained without administered contrast.
FINDINGS: Cervical alignment is normal.Moderate disc narrowing involves C6-C7, and mild disc narrowing is present at C5-C6.The cord shows no intrinsic signal abnormality.
The C3-C4 level shows mild left foraminal narrowing related to mild posterolateral disc protrusion and spurring.
The C4-C5 level shows mild broad-based posterior and posterolateral disc bulging and mild bilateral foraminal narrowing.

The C5-C6 level shows mild broad-based posterior disc protrusion that effaces the anterior thecal sac without cord deformity.The posterior thecal space is maintained at this level.Posterolateral bulging produces mild right foraminal narrowing.
The C6-C7 level shows mild broad-based posterior disc bulging that effaces the antrum thecal sac without cord impingement.Neural foramina appear maintained. The C7-T1 level is unremarkable.

content.content: Comment:

Any value above the 99% upper reference range (>0.04 ng/mL) is an indicator of myocardial necrosis.
Serial testing (baseline and 2-4 hour intervals) may be helpful in assessing ischemic vs. non-ischemic elevations.
Possible non-ischemic causes of elevated troponins:
Tachyarrhythmias, congestive heart failure, critically ill patients (sepsis, respiratory failure, inflammatory diseases, burns), pulmonary embolism or severe pulmonary hypertension, severe hypertension or hypotension, apical ballooning cardiomyopathy
(TakoTsubo Syndrome), stroke or subarachnoid hemmorrhage, renal failure, myocarditis, myopericarditis, cardioversion or
ablations, aortic stenosis, chest trauma, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, coronary spasm, hypothyroidism, infiltrative cardiomyopathy, extreme exertion, drug toxicity (some chemotherapies).

paragraph.content: MRI FOOT LEFT W WO CONTRAST 10/26/2013 12:44:26
PROVIDED HISTORY: Rule out ostoemyelitis left great toe

TECHNIQUE: Sagittal axial and coronal T1 and STIR sequences were obtained.
A fat suppressed proton density sagittal sequence was also obtained.
After giving 16 ml of multi of contrast, fat suppressed T1-weighted
sagittal, axial and coronal sequences
were obtained.
FINDINGS: Abnormal decreased signal is present in the midportion of the
proximal phalanx of the first toe medially. Small foci of rounded
abnormal signal are present in the head of the first metatarsal as well.
The distal phalanx of the first toe has
normal marrow signal. Edema is present in the midportion of the proximal
phalanx of the first toe on the STIR sequence. Soft tissue swelling,
inflammation of the subcutaneous fat and enhancement is noted in the soft
tissues of the first toe, extending
into the webspace between the first and second toes. A discrete abscess
is not identified. There is cortical disruption of the proximal phalanx
medial aspect.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal signal and enhancement with apparent cortical
destruction of the proximal phalanx of the first toe medial aspect, most
likely representing osteomyelitis. There is adjacent cellulitis in the
soft tissues of the first toe extending
into the webspace between the first and second toes. No soft tissue
abscess is identified.
Small rounded focus of abnormal signal in the head of the first metatarsal
could be infection or related to degenerative change.
